description:
## Problem
Managers directly access scene internals, creating tight coupling:
```javascript
// CollisionManager.js
if (this.scene.player.isInvincible) return;
this.scene.gameState.addScore(enemy.points);
this.scene.loseLife();

// BossManager.js
this.scene.gameState.lives++;  // Bypasses any lives management logic
```

This violates Law of Demeter and makes refactoring risky.

## Locations
- `src/systems/CollisionManager.js` - multiple direct accesses
- `src/systems/BossManager.js:154-160` - direct state mutation
- `src/systems/EnemySpawner.js` - scene property access

## Solution
Use events for cross-system communication:
```javascript
// Instead of: this.scene.gameState.addScore(points)
this.scene.events.emit('addScore', points);

// GameScene listens:
this.events.on('addScore', (points) => {
  this.gameState.addScore(points);
  this.uiManager.updateScore(this.gameState.score);
});
```

## Acceptance
- Managers communicate via events, not direct property access
- GameScene is the only class that directly modifies gameState
- Unit testing managers becomes possible with mock event emitter

## Problem
Object pools scattered across GameScene.create():
- bullets pool (line 153)
- enemyBullets pool (line 41)
- mines pool (line 51)
- powerUps pool (line 57)
- enemies pool in EnemySpawner

No consistent interface, hard to see all pools.

## Solution
Create PoolManager:

```javascript
class PoolManager {
  constructor(scene) {
    this.pools = {};
  }

  register(name, classType, config) { ... }
  get(name, x, y) { ... }
  fire(name, x, y, velocity) { ... }
}
```

## Files to change
- src/systems/PoolManager.js (new)
- src/scenes/GameScene.js - use PoolManager
- src/systems/EnemySpawner.js - use PoolManager

## Benefit
Single source of truth for object management

## Problem
Boss.js is 560+ lines with hardcoded attack patterns:
- sprayAttack() 
- aimedAttack()
- ringAttack()
- summonAttack()

Each attack has own cooldown, tween, bullet logic. Adding attacks = editing Boss class.

## Solution
Extract to strategy pattern:

```javascript
// BossAttacks.js
export const SprayAttack = { cooldown: 2000, execute(boss) { ... } }
export const AimedAttack = { cooldown: 1500, execute(boss) { ... } }
export const RingAttack = { cooldown: 3000, execute(boss) { ... } }

// Config
GameConfig.BOSSES.MEGASHIP = {
  phases: [
    { threshold: 1.0, attacks: ['spray', 'aimed'] },
    { threshold: 0.66, attacks: ['spray', 'aimed', 'summon'] },
    { threshold: 0.33, attacks: ['spray', 'aimed', 'ring', 'summon'] }
  ]
}
```

## Files to change
- src/sprites/BossAttacks.js (new)
- src/sprites/Boss.js - use attack registry
- src/config/GameConfig.js - add BOSSES config

## Benefit
New attacks = new strategy file, bosses defined in config

## Problem
Several places access objects that could be null/destroyed:

1. `Boss.js:441-442` - Player could be destroyed during attack:
```javascript
const player = this.scene.player;
if (!player || !player.active) return;
// But player is used again later without re-checking
```

2. `Mine.js` - explode() accesses player without full guard

3. `BossManager.js:154` - boss param in callback could theoretically be null

## Locations
- `src/sprites/Boss.js` - aimedAttack method
- `src/sprites/Mine.js` - explode method
- `src/systems/BossManager.js` - onBossDefeated callback

## Solution
Add defensive checks:
```javascript
// Cache and verify before use
const player = this.scene?.player;
if (!player?.active) return;

// Use optional chaining for callbacks
onBossDefeated(boss) {
  if (!boss) return;
  this.scene.gameState.addScore(boss.points);
}
```

## Acceptance
- No null reference errors during gameplay
- Edge cases (player death during boss attack) handled gracefully
- Game doesn't crash when objects are destroyed mid-action
